Strict, parseable Plover dictionary source for a Steno programming-shorthand system, consumed by `src/parse.ts` — this is the canonical data file; the parser's grammar must stay in lockstep with the operator set documented here.

Each entry is a fenced block: ` ````STROKE ` opens with the chord, the template body follows until the closing fence. An optional `###description` line precedes an entry as documentation only (not parsed as a directive). Directives (`@count KEYS`, `@arity N`, `@multiline`, `@fuse`, `@type`, `@noarg`, `@literal`) attach to the entry immediately above and change how `parse.ts` must interpret its template.

Template operator semantics that `parse.ts` must implement exactly:
- `%0`–`%9`: cursor/tabstop landing points; `%0` is the plain-profile landing, others are snippet tabstops.
- `%d`: emits the in-scope count as a literal digit — the total count outside a `%[...%]` repeat, or the iteration index inside one. Never a landing point.
- `%t`: type-slot, filled when a type stroke (one of the `@type`-marked entries below) is appended to the base stroke.
- `%b`: body-break; all `%b` occurrences in one translation toggle together for the one-liner flag.
- `%p`: pattern-slot.
- `%[ sep | body %]`: repeat construct; `sep` joins iterations and is never emitted trailing the last one.
- `%(EXPR)`: computed landing point, EXPR linear in `d`; the parser must detect numbering conflicts and error rather than silently renumber.
- Escapes: `\n \t \{ \} \% \| \\ \`` must be recognized literally inside templates.

Directive semantics: `@count KEYS` binds the repeat/count bank to specific steno keys (e.g. `AOE`, `AO`) — determines how many repeat iterations a chord can select. `@arity N` (default 0) marks a type entry as requiring N appended type-args before it's complete (e.g. `Map`, `Record`, `Promise`, `Set`, `Array`, `Generator` — anything with arity>0 stays non-terminal until satisfied). `@type` marks an entry as an appendable type suffix, usable after `%t`-bearing strokes or standalone via `STKWR-T`. `@noarg` marks a type with no generic slot ever. `@fuse` means the appended type stroke merges into the base shape stroke rather than requiring an intermediate type-less stroke — affects how `parse.ts` composes multi-stroke entries. `@multiline` marks templates whose `\n` are literal newlines, not governed by `%b`. `@literal` marks whole-file emission blocks (the data-structure classes at the bottom) that are emitted verbatim with no operator substitution beyond `%t`-style generic typing already baked into the TypeScript source.

Key coupling: the STKWR-PBGS function family behaves differently when `@fuse` is present vs absent — absent means a bare type-less function stroke exists as an intermediate state; present (most of them) means the type stroke fuses directly into the shape, skipping that intermediate. The callback method-root family (`STKWR*PLT/...`) encodes a two-stroke root+selector dispatch: first stroke picks "method mode," second selects the specific array/string/math method — order and root chord must match `parse.ts`'s dispatch table or new methods won't resolve. Data structure entries (bottom section, `STKWR-RBGT/...`) are fully literal TypeScript classes with no template substitution; editing one requires updating the literal text exactly, including the generic `<T>` typing convention, since there's no per-field templating mechanism.

If `parse.ts`'s directive or operator table diverges from this list, entries silently fail to parse or misfire — this file and the parser must be edited together.